WEBVTT

00:06.180 --> 00:08.617
Okay, everybody, everybody?
Um, quick heads-up.

00:08.617 --> 00:10.749
I presume some of you may have
heard some of these accusations

00:10.749 --> 00:12.838
that have been flying around
about defective pawls

00:12.838 --> 00:14.144
and a cover-up, et cetera.

00:14.144 --> 00:16.407
Well, if there is
an investigation,

00:16.407 --> 00:19.628
we may receive a "preservation
of evidence" order.

00:19.628 --> 00:23.066
That makes it illegal for you
to destroy any documents, okay?

00:23.066 --> 00:26.200
Second heads-up: we actually
haven't received one yet, okay?

00:26.200 --> 00:28.071
So, um, you know,
at this moment in time,

00:28.071 --> 00:32.075
the destruction of documents
is not presently a crime, so...

00:34.077 --> 00:35.513
Our stock's already down 20%.

00:35.513 --> 00:36.949
This is the worst day
of my life.

00:36.949 --> 00:38.777
Yeah, a lot of people
are hurting right now.

00:38.777 --> 00:40.431
Yeah, but I'm being hurt
the most, you know,

00:40.431 --> 00:42.912
'cause I own the most stock.
- Huge discovery this morning:

00:42.912 --> 00:45.306
McDonald's sells bagels.
- Hmm.

00:45.306 --> 00:46.481
How you guys holding up?

00:46.481 --> 00:48.091
I may have to get rid
of Rosalita.

00:48.091 --> 00:49.701
- Your housekeeper?
- What? No.

00:49.701 --> 00:52.008
Mayra's my housekeeper, and
sometimes her daughter helps.

00:52.008 --> 00:53.183
Rosalita's my catamaran.

00:53.183 --> 00:54.793
She's a 42-foot Crowther,

00:54.793 --> 00:57.100
and now I don't know
if I can afford to keep her.

00:57.100 --> 00:59.885
- Wow.
- Yes, not fair, exactly.

00:59.885 --> 01:01.148
If you have deleted

01:01.148 --> 01:02.975
any sensitive files
off your computer,

01:02.975 --> 01:05.804
don't worry: the authorities
will be able to retrieve them,

01:05.804 --> 01:07.850
you know, unless you happen
to run your hard drive

01:07.850 --> 01:09.939
through an industrial-grade
degausser...

01:09.939 --> 01:11.549
Like the one located

01:11.549 --> 01:13.377
in room 261
of the IT department.

01:13.377 --> 01:14.726
Now, some of you
may be wondering,

01:14.726 --> 01:16.902
"Elliot, what's
with the power drill?"

01:18.687 --> 01:20.906
<i>♪ Bom bom
bom-bom-bom-bom-bom ♪</i>

01:20.906 --> 01:23.866
<i>♪ Buh buh bom-bom-bom
buh bom-bom-bom-bom ♪</i>

01:26.695 --> 01:29.393
All right,
for the next couple of days,

01:29.393 --> 01:31.395
or as long
as this little crisis lasts,

01:31.395 --> 01:34.398
this is officially our...

01:34.398 --> 01:36.139
- Wah-room?
- What?

01:36.139 --> 01:38.141
No, war room.

01:38.141 --> 01:39.316
It does look like wah-room.

01:39.316 --> 01:40.535
- Yeah.
- You want me to rewrite it?

01:40.535 --> 01:41.536
Everyone knows what it says,
all right?

01:41.536 --> 01:42.754
Will you just put it up, please?

01:42.754 --> 01:43.886
You want me to take it
to the print shop?

01:43.886 --> 01:45.017
I can make it look
more professional.

01:45.017 --> 01:46.454
Eh, don't bother.

01:46.454 --> 01:47.716
By the time they finish,
this thing will all be over.

01:47.716 --> 01:49.152
Oh, everyone's
met Ian, right?

01:49.152 --> 01:50.936
He's the best crisis manager
out there.

01:50.936 --> 01:53.287
He got us through a lot
of thorny stuff at York,

01:53.287 --> 01:55.767
and he has also worked with--
- Eh, bah-bah-bah.

01:55.767 --> 01:57.291
We don't talk
about other clients,

01:57.291 --> 01:59.336
but let's just say
I am his top gun,

01:59.336 --> 02:03.210
and to make him seem normal
is a mission impossible.

02:03.210 --> 02:05.212
All right, so we are
in very good hands.

02:05.212 --> 02:06.430
All right, my SEO guys

02:06.430 --> 02:07.605
are working to choke
this story out.

02:07.605 --> 02:09.433
When you Google
"Payne scandal,"

02:09.433 --> 02:11.783
all you're gonna get
is 15 articles on Wesley

02:11.783 --> 02:13.568
going to a college
Halloween party

02:13.568 --> 02:14.873
dressed as Whoopi Goldberg.
- Oh...

02:14.873 --> 02:17.702
It wasn't Whoopi.
I was a Rasta guy.

02:17.702 --> 02:19.443
All right, where are we
with the bad pawls?

02:19.443 --> 02:21.097
- That's some good news.
- Mm.

02:21.097 --> 02:22.359
We stress-tested them,

02:22.359 --> 02:23.882
and even though they weren't
technically rated

02:23.882 --> 02:26.581
for the weight of the Hydra,
they were able to hold it.

02:26.581 --> 02:28.148
I went on the NHTSA database,
all right?

02:28.148 --> 02:29.714
Prior to the interview airing,

02:29.714 --> 02:31.629
the number of complaints about
Hydras rolling out of park

02:31.629 --> 02:33.501
was in line with any other car.
- Okay, score one.

02:33.501 --> 02:35.633
Just because nothing terrible
has happened yet

02:35.633 --> 02:37.069
doesn't mean it's not going to.

02:37.069 --> 02:38.636
I think we should still do
the recall, to be safe.

02:38.636 --> 02:40.334
I agree.
We should get ahead of this.

02:40.334 --> 02:42.988
Shocker--Jack and Sadie
are on the same side.

02:42.988 --> 02:44.468
It's like, "Have sex already."

02:44.468 --> 02:46.296
I mean,
you already did have sex,

02:46.296 --> 02:47.776
so it's like,
"Do it again already,"

02:47.776 --> 02:49.821
in front of us or something--
could you imagine?

02:49.821 --> 02:51.519
Here's my card
for when you need it.

02:51.519 --> 02:53.390
It's gonna look shady if I go
to the press and I say,

02:53.390 --> 02:54.739
"Oh, the pawls totally work.

02:54.739 --> 02:56.698
Oh, but, also,
we're doing a recall."

02:56.698 --> 02:58.830
Yeah, you shouldn't be
talking to the press at all.

02:58.830 --> 03:01.311
Anyone we throw out there
right now would be savaged.

03:01.311 --> 03:02.965
Oh, yeah,
like one of those videos

03:02.965 --> 03:06.316
where you see, like,
a bear tear a person apart.

03:06.316 --> 03:08.492
Uh, it's normally in Russia,
so don't worry.

03:08.492 --> 03:09.885
- Oh.
- All right, if somebody's

03:09.885 --> 03:11.800
gonna jump on the grenade,
it should be me.

03:11.800 --> 03:13.497
Great, 'cause I was gonna say
that I could do it, but--

03:13.497 --> 03:14.803
Fine.
Sadie'll talk to the press.

03:14.803 --> 03:16.021
You said you'd--

03:16.021 --> 03:17.153
Yeah, I'll do it.

03:17.153 --> 03:18.546
Love to. Happy to.
- Okay, perfect.

03:18.546 --> 03:19.938
I know this is stressful,

03:19.938 --> 03:22.506
but if there is one thing
that I know about myself,

03:22.506 --> 03:24.204
it is that I don't lose.
- Mm-hmm.

03:24.204 --> 03:25.509
We will get through this.

03:26.858 --> 03:29.513
Oh, [bleep].
Jesus, that's awful.

03:29.513 --> 03:31.211
Oh, it's just
how I imagined it.

03:33.778 --> 03:35.998
- Second breakfast?
- Third.

03:35.998 --> 03:37.478
I eat when I'm stressed.

03:37.478 --> 03:39.654
I was up all night Googling
corporate scandals.

03:39.654 --> 03:41.699
People go to jail.

03:41.699 --> 03:43.875
This isn't some giant
pyramid scheme, all right?

03:43.875 --> 03:46.095
We--we put a wonky part
in a few mid-range crossovers

03:46.095 --> 03:47.444
and got called out for it.

03:47.444 --> 03:49.011
So you're not worried
they'll need a fall guy

03:49.011 --> 03:50.360
and it could be one of us?

03:50.360 --> 03:51.883
Well, it's not gonna be me.

03:51.883 --> 03:53.668
Anytime I find myself
in a legally dubious situation,

03:53.668 --> 03:55.583
I write myself
a contemporaneous memo.

03:55.583 --> 03:58.281
So I have one dated from that
night saved on my computer

03:58.281 --> 04:00.283
saying that I advocated
for a recall.

04:00.283 --> 04:02.111
But you said
we shouldn't do a recall.

04:02.111 --> 04:04.374
Oh, Cyrus.

04:04.374 --> 04:06.724
That's not how my memo
remembers it.

04:06.724 --> 04:08.291
Ta-ta.

04:08.291 --> 04:09.901
Ugh. I hate this.

04:09.901 --> 04:11.642
Why'd you volunteer
if you didn't want to do it?

04:11.642 --> 04:13.644
I was trying to look good
in front of Katherine.

04:13.644 --> 04:15.777
I mean, it's like offering
to split the check on a date.

04:15.777 --> 04:17.605
You don't think they're gonna
take you up on that.

04:17.605 --> 04:19.520
Uh, I let the lady pay
for the whole thing.

04:19.520 --> 04:20.738
It shows that I'm worth it.

04:20.738 --> 04:22.610
Knock, knock.
Ready to face the mob?

04:22.610 --> 04:24.655
Yes, just going over
my statement here.

04:24.655 --> 04:27.832
Great.
Let me take a look here.

04:27.832 --> 04:29.312
No.

04:29.312 --> 04:31.271
Nope. Uh-uh.

04:31.271 --> 04:33.621
Huh-uh. Huh-uh.

04:33.621 --> 04:34.883
Uh-uh.

04:34.883 --> 04:35.710
All right.

04:35.710 --> 04:37.364
There you go. Godspeed.

04:37.364 --> 04:39.104
Ian, you kind of crossed out
a lot here.

04:39.104 --> 04:40.541
I'm sorry, Sadie.

04:40.541 --> 04:41.716
How many companies
have you saved from bankruptcy?

04:41.716 --> 04:43.718
Um, to my knowledge, zero.

04:43.718 --> 04:45.372
And I'm assuming most
of the press conferences you do

04:45.372 --> 04:46.590
are cutesy fun things,

04:46.590 --> 04:48.157
like factory openings,
charity events,

04:48.157 --> 04:49.985
where wheelchair kids
get to meet John Cena.

04:49.985 --> 04:51.769
We don't call them
"wheelchair kids."

04:51.769 --> 04:52.988
Fine, but you're
in my world now,

04:52.988 --> 04:53.945
where the more you say,

04:53.945 --> 04:55.120
the more they can attack.

04:55.120 --> 04:57.209
So you say nothing
and admit even less.

04:57.209 --> 04:58.341
Got it?

05:00.604 --> 05:02.780
We just call them kids.

05:02.780 --> 05:04.478
See, I wrote the memo
months ago.

05:04.478 --> 05:06.654
It was about how I wanted
to recall the Hydra,

05:06.654 --> 05:09.091
but for some reason,
it says I wrote it today,

05:09.091 --> 05:11.920
and I need it to say
I wrote it back then.

05:11.920 --> 05:13.835
So you want me

05:13.835 --> 05:16.359
to violate the fundamental
rules of space-time?

05:16.359 --> 05:18.579
That's a good one.

05:18.579 --> 05:19.928
